            USER DATA 

                - When launching an Amazon EC2 instance, you can provide a User Data script. User Data is a script that automatically runs the first time an EC2 instance starts. It is commonly used to bootstrap an instance, meaning it performs initial setup tasks without requiring manual intervention. This allows every new instance to be configured consistently as soon as it launches.

                - User Data can automate a wide variety of setup tasks. For example, it can install the latest operating system updates and security patches, install software such as Nginx, Apache, Docker, or application dependencies, download files from the internet, retrieve configuration files, or deploy application code. By automating these tasks, the instance is fully configured and ready to use immediately after startup.

                - One important characteristic of User Data is that it runs with root privileges, meaning it has full administrative access to the operating system. Because of this, the script can make system-wide changes, such as installing packages, modifying configuration files, and starting services. While this provides great flexibility, it also means that User Data scripts should be written carefully to avoid introducing security risks or configuration errors.

                - By default, the User Data script runs only once, during the instance's initial boot. After the instance has been created, the script will not run again unless it is specifically configured to do so or the instance is recreated with new User Data. This makes it ideal for one-time initialization tasks rather than ongoing administration.

                - For DevOps engineers, EC2 User Data is an essential automation tool. In environments where dozens or even hundreds of EC2 instances are deployed, manually logging into each server to perform setup tasks would be inefficient and time-consuming. Instead, User Data allows these tasks to be defined once and executed automatically on every new instance. This improves consistency, reduces manual effort, minimizes human error, and helps automate application deployments and infrastructure provisioning at scale.
                


            EC2 INSTANCE TYPE 
                -	Aws offers different types of EC2 instances depending on what your are trying to do.
                
                -	1) EC2 instance types define the kind of hardware your virtual machine uses. Not all EC2 instances are the same—Amazon Web Services offers different instance types so you can choose the right one for your workload. The goal is simple: use the right tool for the job.

                -	2) General Purpose instances are the most commonly used. They provide a balanced mix of CPU, memory, and networking, making them suitable for web servers, small databases, development environments, and other everyday workloads.

                -	3) Compute Optimized instances are designed for workloads that need a lot of processing power. These instances provide more CPU relative to memory and are ideal for tasks such as batch processing, high-performance computing, and heavy calculations.

                -	4) Memory Optimized instances focus on providing large amounts of RAM. They are best for applications that need to hold a lot of data in memory, such as in-memory databases, big data processing, and certain high-performance workloads.

                -	4) Storage Optimized instances are built for fast and high-throughput storage access. They are well suited for large datasets, data warehouses, and databases that require very fast read and write performance.

                -	5) Accelerated Computing instances include specialized hardware such as GPUs and FPGAs. These are commonly used for machine learning, video rendering, scientific simulations, and other compute-intensive workloads that benefit from hardware acceleration.

                -	6) HPC Optimized instances (High-Performance Computing) are designed for extremely demanding workloads. They combine powerful processors with high-speed networking, making them ideal for scientific modeling, simulations, and large-scale compute tasks.

                -	7) AWS instance names follow a clear naming convention. For example, in M5.2xlarge, the M represents the instance class (General Purpose), the 5 indicates the generation, and 2xlarge defines the size, which determines how much CPU and memory the instance has.

                -	8) Choosing the right EC2 instance type is a balancing act between performance and cost. If the instance is too small, your application may struggle. If it’s too large, you end up paying for resources you don’t need. The best choice matches your workload requirements as closely as possible. 


            EC2 INSTANCES PURCHASING OPTIONS

                - ON DEMAND INSTANCES: this instance type is optimal for shortterm/unpredictable workloads, where you want predictable prices and no long term commitments paying by the second making it highly flexible, it isnt always the cheapest option.

                - RESERVED INSTANCES: this could be from 1-3 years, the longer it is the cheaper the price, this is optimal for when you are running a steady workload for a longer period of time this instance will offer a bigger discount in exchange for time commited. There are two types of reserved instances the standard one and a convertable resevered instances which give you flexablilty and change instance time overtime 

                - Savings Plans provide discounted EC2 pricing in exchange for committing to a consistent amount of compute usage over a one-year or three-year term. They offer similar savings to Reserved Instances but with greater flexibility, allowing you to change instance families, instance sizes, operating systems, or AWS Regions while still receiving the discount. Savings Plans are an excellent choice for organizations with long-term workloads that may evolve over time.

                - Spot Instances allow you to use unused EC2 capacity at significantly reduced prices, often up to 90% cheaper than On-Demand Instances. The trade-off is that AWS can interrupt or terminate a Spot Instance with short notice whenever the capacity is needed elsewhere. As a result, Spot Instances are best suited for fault-tolerant or interruptible workloads, such as batch processing, data analysis, image rendering, testing, and distributed computing.

                - Dedicated Hosts provide an entire physical server that is dedicated exclusively to your AWS account. Because you have visibility into the underlying hardware, Dedicated Hosts are commonly used to meet software licensing requirements or regulatory and compliance obligations that require applications to run on dedicated physical hardware.

                - Dedicated Instances also run on hardware dedicated to a single AWS customer, meaning the underlying server is not shared with other AWS accounts. However, unlike Dedicated Hosts, you do not have control or visibility over the specific physical server on which your instances are running. Dedicated Instances are typically used when workload isolation is required for security or compliance purposes without needing direct management of the host.

                - Capacity Reservations allow you to reserve EC2 capacity in a specific Availability Zone for a specified instance type. This ensures that capacity will always be available when you need to launch instances, even during periods of high demand. Capacity Reservations are particularly useful for business-critical applications that require guaranteed availability and cannot risk failing to launch due to insufficient EC2 capacity.

                - Selecting the appropriate purchasing option can significantly reduce costs while meeting your application's availability and performance requirements. On-Demand Instances are best suited for short-term or unpredictable workloads, Savings Plans are ideal for long-term workloads that require flexibility, Reserved Instances are appropriate for predictable long-term usage, Spot Instances provide the lowest cost for interruptible workloads, Dedicated Hosts and Dedicated Instances are designed for isolation and compliance, and Capacity Reservations guarantee compute capacity when availability is critical.
